INSERT INTO mendezPharmacy VALUES (15, "Metformin 1000mg", 11, 100, 2);

-- Summary statistic query
-- Groups meds by name & price, then sums the quantity to show total stock.  
-- This helps quickly see how much inventory exists at each price point.
SELECT 
    name, 
    Price_in_dollars, 
    SUM(quantity) AS total_quantity
FROM mendezPharmacy
GROUP BY name, Price_in_dollars
ORDER BY Price_in_dollars;

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
## Original Assignment
Create a store database with:
At least one table
At least five columns
At least 15 items
A query that orders items by price
A query that calculates at least one statistic

Technologies Used
SQL

## Features
-- Fully structured pharmacy inventory table with 5 meaningful columns.
-- Dataset of 15 medications with real-world drug names and stock levels.
-- Sorting by price to identify the cheapest or most expensive medications.
-- Summary query using SUM() to reveal total inventory per medication.

## What I Learned
-- I learned how to design a functional SQL table and populate it with realistic data. I also practiced using grouping and aggregate functions to analyze inventory. 
-- The biggest takeaway was understanding how ordering and summarizing data can support real operational decisions, like stocking, pricing, and supply tracking.

## How It Can Be Improved
-- Add a last_date_purchased column for tracking recent activity.
-- Auto-increment the id field to remove manual numbering.
-- Add a category or manufacturer column for more detailed analytics.
